{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/varicocele/diagnosis/clinical-features-of-varicocele/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"ce3fe174-add9-5c82-b0e9-1242a96030c9","slug":"clinical-features-of-varicocele","fullItemName":"Clinical features of varicocele","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 839cc1d0-d71f-459a-afa4-ff78244e9f41 --><h2>What are the clinical features of varicocele?</h2><!-- end field 839cc1d0-d71f-459a-afa4-ff78244e9f41 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item b2863fac-872e-4e9d-81fe-2124ec6a7c60 --><!-- begin field b17a0e7c-74cf-49db-8178-a71b00b143ca --><ul><li>Painless scrotal swelling on the left side — 90% of varicoceles appear on the left.<ul><li>Scrotal or groin pain (uncommon) — less than 3% of men with varicocele have pain, or dragging or heavy sensations in the scrotum.</li><li>A right-sided varicocele alone is rare and should be referred to a urologist.</li></ul></li><li>A varicocele presents characteristically as a 'bag of worms' within the spermatic cord above the testis on the left side of the scrotum:<ul><li>The scrotum on the side of the varicocele may be seen to hang lower than on the normal side.</li><li>Dilation and tortuosity of the veins is increased on standing and is usually decreased when the man lies down. The varicocele cannot usually be palpated lying down.</li><li>Performing the Valsalva manoeuvre whilst standing increases dilation.</li><li>There may be a cough impulse.</li></ul></li><li>Small testis — larger varicoceles are associated with a higher incidence of testicular growth arrest in adolescents.<ul><li>Surgical correction may reverse this.</li></ul></li><li>Aged older than 12 years — varicoceles occur in 15% of adolescent boys and adult men.<ul><li>Varicoceles are rare in pre-pubertal boys (aged less than 12 years).</li></ul></li><li>Infertility — approximately one in four men with abnormal semen parameters will have a varicocele, and 40% of men presenting with infertility have a varicocele.</li><li>If there is uncertainty about the diagnosis, see the section on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/scrotal-pain-swelling/background-information/causes/\">causes of scrotal swelling</a> in the CKS topic on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/scrotal-pain-swelling/\">Scrotal pain and swelling</a>.</li></ul><!-- end field b17a0e7c-74cf-49db-8178-a71b00b143ca --><!-- end item b2863fac-872e-4e9d-81fe-2124ec6a7c60 -->","topic":{"id":"5977adfa-83aa-58a5-a712-0d4298766144","topicId":"466ec4b4-92f7-47d6-bfd7-b3b0ab41036b","topicName":"Varicocele","slug":"varicocele","lastRevised":"Last revised in April 2017","chapters":[{"id":"d0689845-07d1-5161-80e9-84ff77e5ad2b","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"d51b0e4c-521b-58bd-888f-f5dc2ebe6261","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"4580547c-b151-50d5-8dad-17550c8c7e58","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"4100bf94-3d55-5054-af0b-12a9a5df0db4","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"c7dd5fe2-22e0-5a96-a24e-68c9472ea09d","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"43488552-18c6-5033-977d-30d7c76c4dae","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"790589a4-32e2-5b89-9031-bdbbb1f5ff33","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"9a1cee3d-509b-5b2a-aef9-4371a66e36b7","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"891b532f-f746-5aef-8d40-5b97a41b8f40","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"f49848ab-01c1-52c1-8f76-c1b5da1fd757","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"b853589c-b4e3-548a-816e-c2926684bb4b","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP - Options for local implementation"},{"id